WEBVTT

00:00:00.031 --> 00:00:14.090
SPEAKER_00: In 1912, fragments from a gravel pit in Sussex seemed to give British science the fossil it wanted, a human-like skull, an ape-like jaw, a famous name, Piltdown Man.

00:00:15.201 --> 00:00:18.085
SPEAKER_00: The evidence was thin, but the story was powerful.

00:00:19.167 --> 00:00:23.594
SPEAKER_00: It fit a brain-first theory and gave Britain its own ancient ancestor.

00:00:24.435 --> 00:00:34.070
SPEAKER_00: Some anatomists doubted the skull and jaw belonged together, but access was limited, prestige was heavy, and the specimen kept circulating as authority.

00:00:34.771 --> 00:00:36.033
SPEAKER_00: The fraud was not perfect.

00:00:36.774 --> 00:00:37.435
SPEAKER_00: It was welcome.

00:00:38.417 --> 00:00:42.323
SPEAKER_00: By 1953, Tess exposed the trick.

00:00:42.302 --> 00:00:44.189
SPEAKER_00: The skull was a recent human bone.

00:00:44.993 --> 00:00:46.537
SPEAKER_00: The jaw was from an orangutan.

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:48.505
SPEAKER_00: The teeth had been filed.

00:00:49.106 --> 00:00:50.392
SPEAKER_00: The bones had been stained.

00:00:51.113 --> 00:00:54.365
SPEAKER_00: The hoax survived because it let the field feel correct.

00:00:55.289 --> 00:00:56.353
SPEAKER_00: The mystery fades.

00:00:56.975 --> 00:00:58.320
SPEAKER_00: The receipts remain.
